***** Important security advisory *****

Dear Sir or Madam,

POP3 (Post Office Protocol version 3) is a network protocol for retrieving
email messages from an email server. The client/server connection is usually
encrypted using TLS. Alternatively, an unencrypted connection can be
established first and then turned into an encrypted connection using the
"STLS" extension.

POP3 provides different mechanisms for authentication.
With "PLAIN" and "LOGIN", login credentials (username and password) are sent
in plain text (just base64-encoded).

If the server does not provide TLS-encrypted connections and only offers
"PLAIN" and "LOGIN" as authentication mechanisms, the client needs to send
the login credentials in plain text to the server.
In this case, attackers can potentially sniff the login credentials from
the network and gain unauthorized access to email accounts.

CERT-Bund strongly recommends changing the POP3 server configuration so that
authentication using "PLAIN" or "LOGIN" is only accepted with TLS connections.
If the POP3 server is no longer used, it should be disabled.

